1 Historical Background
The concept of eld emission, as proposed by Fowler and Nordheim in 1928 [1], was
a fundamental breakthrough in understanding the emission of electrons from solid-state
materials when subjected to a strong electric eld. This theoretical work laid the ground-
work for various applications in electron microscopy, including the development of the
Field Emission Microscope (FEM). Following is the Fowler-Nordheim equation for the
emission current density (J) from the surface
J = E
2
exp
E
where is a constant, is the work-function, E is the local eld intensity.
In 1936, Erwin Wilhelm Muller, a German physicist, was the rst person to experimen-
tally observe emission of electrons from a tungsten surface covered with barium [3]. These
electrons were soon employed in many dierent techniques, most important of which was
the Electron Microscopy. During late 1930s, Johnson and Shockley [2] investigated the
eld emission from a lamentous wire inside cylindrical tube with partially conducting
uorescent screen. This setup oered magnication of the order of the ratio of radius of
tube to the radius of wire.
During the next two decades the investigation of various emission sources for improving
the resolution of the established Electron Microscopy techniques led scientists to discover
the ability of emission electrons to map the surface if emitted from a tip under a radial
eld, this led to the birth of Field Emission Microscope. This technique was utilised
to achieve ultra high magnication of pointed surfaces of various materials. Further
the derivatives that combined various techniques with/using eld-emission electrons have
been developed (FE-SEM, FIM etc.) through out the 20th century
2 Analysis of Observed K-space patterns
Since, the nature of the following experiment is quite qualitative, as compared to other
experiments being quantitative, the best we can do is analyse the observed patterns and
infer the underlying physics. We performed our experiment with the following goals-
1. Observing the image of the tungsten tip lattice on the uorescent screen. But this
requires the cleaning of the tungsten tip by baking it using a heating current. An
important point to remember while baking the tungsten tip is that we need to bake
it for 10-15 mins instead of 5 minutes as written in the manual.
2. Checking how the pattern of the tungsten tip on the uorescent screen changes with
changing voltage.
3. Deciphering the miller indices of the crystallographic planes as observed as the dark
spots on the screen.
4. Observing how the pattern changes with time

Quantum Tunneling It is a fundamental quantum physics phenomenon where
particles, such as electrons, can overcome barriers that classical physics deems im-
passable. This intriguing behavior arises from the inherent uncertainty in a par-
ticles position and energy at the quantum level. Occasionally, particles exploit
this uncertainty to appear on the other side of an obstacle, defying our classical
intuitions.
Figure 1: Tunneling Current
Variable work functions along dierent crystallographic planes Tungsten
has a body-centred cubic lattice. The crystallographic direction [1 1 0] points to
the centre of the uorescent screen since it is due to the way of preparation of the
crystal. [1 0 0] and [0 1 0] point upwards and downwards. Along these directions
of low index, crystals have high work functions and hence upon mapping onto the
uorescent screen, they form dark spots.

From the above three observed patterns, we can infer the following observations-
The rst pattern is clearer than the second pattern. This is due to the fact the
rst pattern was observed immediately after baking. And the second pattern was
observed after sometime. Due to deposition of vapour on the tungsten tip with time,
the crystallographic structure of the tungsten tip is perturbed causing blurring of
the pattern.
The 3rd image is clearer and dierent from the other two images. This is due to
the fact that 3rd pattern is observed on a dierent set-up and the tungsten tip may
have a slight dierent geometry. Also during the 3rd part, the tungsten tip was
baked better than the other two times.
Now, in all the three images, there are alternate dark and bright spots, and they
basic structure is similar in all the three. The main reason for this alternate pattern
is the variation of the local work function across the tungsten crystal depending on
factors such as the density of atoms locally. This depends on the crystal structure. Since,
we are using a tungsten crystal in all the three cases, we got an overall similar pattern.
Regions with lower work function emit a greater number of highly energetic electron-
which correspond to the bright area. While regions of the high work function correspond
to the dark regions.
The numbers written on the dierent parts of the pattern like [1 1 0] refer to the
Miller indices- which are planes of the tungsten crystal with a normal in that direction
(the three spots just refer to the 3 axes)
We notice that the planes [2 1 1], [1 2 1], [1 1 2], [2 1 -1], [1 2 -1] and [1 1 -2] appear
dark, and based on the crystal structure of the tungsten tip and its symmetry, that these
planes are equivalent to each other and to [1 1 0] but the size of the former dark spots
is smaller since the solid angle projected at the uorescent screen is smaller.
On the other hand, the [1 1 1] and [1 1 -1] planes seem to be the brightest and hence
are equivalent by symmetry of the crystal, implying they have the least work function

Finally, on closer inspection, we notice that the [1 0 0] and [0 1 0] planes seem to be
bright but of lower intensity when compared to [1 1 1] which might imply that they have
a work function which is slightly higher but it might also be a consequence of the solid
angle subtended by them on the screen.

3 Discussion
The magnication of a spherical FEM depends on the radius of the tip and the radius of
screen, while the Resolving Power depends upon the uniformity of the tip surface, voltage
applied.
The quality of image depends heavily on the state of the surface of the tip and presence
of any adsorbate on the surface and hence baking is an essential part to be able to see
crisp image.
